WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:48.000
<v Tom Harris>Hello fellow passengers, welcome to the Compass podcast. Today, we are joined by Dr. Nolan Grayson, a quantum physicist whose groundbreaking work on quantum determinism is shaking up everything we thought we knew about free will. His latest book, Quantum Nirvana: How to Achieve Free Will in a Multiverse, dives into the radical idea that maybe, just maybe, you can outsmart quantum determinism. Dr. Grayson, welcome to the show.

00:48.000 --> 03:12.000
<v Dr. Nolan Grayson>Thank you for having me. I always say if I'm going to shatter someone's idea of reality, I prefer to do it with a microphone.

03:12.000 --> 03:18.000
<v Tom Harris>Let's start with the basics. What exactly is quantum determinism?

03:18.000 --> 04:02.000
<v Dr. Nolan Grayson>It's the idea that, at the quantum level, every action is not just influenced by probability but actually determined by quantum states. When you decide to pick up your coffee mug or accidentally send a text to your ex — those decisions are echoing across multiple realities. It's all happening simultaneously in what's called a superposition of outcomes.

04:02.000 --> 04:07.000
<v Tom Harris>So, I'm both making a great decision and a terrible decision at the same time?

04:07.000 --> 08:20.000
<v Dr. Nolan Grayson>Exactly! And in some universe, you also just spilled that coffee on your laptop.

08:20.000 --> 08:25.000
<v Tom Harris>Wow, okay! So tell me about the Superposition Trap. That sounds…ominous.

08:25.000 --> 08:57.000
<v Dr. Nolan Grayson>It is! The Superposition Trap is the idea that because all versions of you are playing out simultaneously, you're effectively paralyzed. You can't not make every choice. Free will is just the illusion that you're picking one path when in reality, you're living out all paths.

08:57.000 --> 09:02.000
<v Tom Harris>So I'm basically doomed to make every mistake possible?

09:02.000 --> 13:45.000
<v Dr. Nolan Grayson>Not just every mistake — every triumph too. But yes, it does complicate the idea of personal accountability, doesn't it?

13:45.000 --> 13:50.000
<v Tom Harris>So when I choose to hit the snooze button, I'm also simultaneously waking up bright and early in some other universe?

13:50.000 --> 14:22.000
<v Dr. Nolan Grayson>Absolutely. Every decision splinters into infinite versions of you, living out every possibility. Some are thriving, some are…well, let's just say, not so much.

14:22.000 --> 14:27.000
<v Tom Harris>That's a lot of pressure. Is there a version of me that's ruling the world?

14:27.000 --> 19:30.000
<v Dr. Nolan Grayson>Statistically speaking, yes. And there's also probably one that's still trying to find its keys from 2014.

19:30.000 --> 19:36.000
<v Tom Harris>Let's talk about quantum entanglement. How does it fit into this idea of choice?

19:36.000 --> 20:12.000
<v Dr. Nolan Grayson>Entanglement is like the universe's cruel joke on autonomy. Two particles become linked, and whatever happens to one instantaneously affects the other, no matter the distance. It's like the universe nudging you every time you think you're making an independent choice.

20:12.000 --> 20:17.000
<v Tom Harris>So my choices are basically tethered to some cosmic dice roll?

20:17.000 --> 25:10.000
<v Dr. Nolan Grayson>In a sense, yes. You might think you're deciding to text someone or take a different route to work, but quantum entanglement suggests your choices might already be synchronized with distant events you can't even perceive.

25:10.000 --> 25:18.000
<v Tom Harris>This brings us to quantum lock-in. Are we stuck in some kind of predetermined path?

25:18.000 --> 25:45.000
<v Dr. Nolan Grayson>That's exactly the idea. Quantum lock-in is when all your possible decisions collapse into a single outcome. You think you're choosing freely, but at the quantum level, everything's been nudged and guided by previous states, like dominoes falling in perfect sequence.

25:45.000 --> 25:48.000
<v Tom Harris>So, there's really no escape?

25:48.000 --> 30:00.000
<v Dr. Nolan Grayson>Not unless you introduce some chaos — quantum noise, for example, can shake things up.

30:00.000 --> 30:05.000
<v Tom Harris>Quantum noise? That sounds like static in the universe.

30:05.000 --> 30:32.000
<v Dr. Nolan Grayson>In a way, it is. Quantum noise disrupts deterministic patterns, introducing randomness that can actually open up new paths. It's the closest thing to true freedom at the quantum level.

30:32.000 --> 30:36.000
<v Tom Harris>So, chaos is my only hope?

30:36.000 --> 35:40.000
<v Dr. Nolan Grayson>If you want to break the cycle, yes. Embrace the chaos.

35:40.000 --> 35:46.000
<v Tom Harris>That's mind boggling. Let's move on to your theory of Quantum Nirvana. It sounds almost spiritual?

35:46.000 --> 41:15.000
<v Dr. Nolan Grayson>It kind of is! Quantum Nirvana is the state of existing simultaneously across all parallel universes with full awareness. Instead of being locked into one outcome, you experience them all — every possibility, every choice — consciously navigating through each path. I know that might sound exhausting, but it's not; it's enlightening. When you can see all those paths laid out before you, you can finally choose which one to focus on. It's like stepping outside the maze and seeing the whole thing at once. That kind of awareness — the ability to consciously decide which version of reality you want to experience — that's as close to true free will as it gets.

41:15.000 --> 41:22.000
<v Tom Harris>There's so much I want to get to. Hacking the multiverse — this sounds like something out of a sci-fi movie. Is it really possible?

41:22.000 --> 41:50.000
<v Dr. Nolan Grayson>Not only is it possible, it's happening right now. Quantum alignment is about syncing your actions with the versions of you that are succeeding across universes. With enough awareness, you can choose which version of reality you want to lean into.

41:50.000 --> 41:54.000
<v Tom Harris>So I can just pick the 'me' that's thriving?

41:54.000 --> 47:25.000
<v Dr. Nolan Grayson>With the right techniques, yes. It's not about jumping universes but aligning with them. Think of it as tuning a radio to the right frequency.

47:25.000 --> 47:28.000
<v Tom Harris>That makes a ton of sense. Alright, lightning round! Favorite thought experiment?

47:28.000 --> 47:34.000
<v Dr. Nolan Grayson>Schrödinger's cat. I like the idea of both being alive and dead until someone bothers to look.

47:34.000 --> 47:36.000
<v Tom Harris>Book recommendation?

47:36.000 --> 47:42.000
<v Dr. Nolan Grayson>The Fabric of Reality by David Deutsch. It's mind-bending in the best way.

47:42.000 --> 47:45.000
<v Tom Harris>What's a routine you swear by?

47:45.000 --> 52:10.000
<v Dr. Nolan Grayson>Meditation. Helps me align with the best version of me — hopefully, the one that remembers to eat breakfast.

52:10.000 --> 52:15.000
<v Tom Harris>Any final thoughts on where all this quantum exploration is leading?

52:15.000 --> 57:30.000
<v Dr. Nolan Grayson>I think it's leading us to realize that free will isn't about picking one path, it's about understanding all of them. When you can see the threads, you can start to weave your own fate.

57:30.000 --> 01:02:00.000
<v Tom Harris>Dr. Grayson, this has been incredible. Where can people find you and your work?

01:02:00.000 --> 01:03:29.000
<v Dr. Nolan Grayson>My website, nolangraysonquantum.com, and of course, my book Quantum Nirvana is available everywhere books are sold.
